@WTGHookie There is a way to lessen motion sickness... keep playing!  Only a selection of people experience motion sickness with VR from the outset, and most of these get past that sickness after a couple of weeks by playing in short bursts... after that they can spend hours in RIGS or Robinson without even breaking a sweat.
Teleportation kills the immersion and is just not necessary... by all means give both options, but to omit free-movement entirely is just keeping the medium held back.
And no... you don't need a 360 treadmill for free-movement... just a DS4 like any other game.

@FortescueHaljournon @WTGHookie  That doesn't always work. There are some people who still get naturally motion sick playing regular games on a 2D television. People's difference in motion sickness is vastly different across the board. I mean, are you really telling me people who get motion sickness driving in a car just need to keep driving in a car, despite having driven and ridden in a car for decades of their life already?

A DS4 causes a disconnect within the body. Your mind sees you are moving but your proprioception and equilibrioception (bodily awareness sense and balance/equilibrium sense, respectively) do not coincide with that, which is what causes the disconnect. Which is why more people get sick with DS4 movement compared to teleporting. Now, a game like RIGS or Battlezone can help trick that feeling, because you are in a vehicle, sitting down, which mimics you sitting down in a chair playing, so your body's proprioception and equilibrioception feel compensated for.

This is the same exact reason why they also have the "floating hands" instead of hands connected to an arm reaching back towards your body in VR games. Because your arms and my arms and the guy's arms in the game are not the same; they are not in the same place or the same length or move identically to each other. So, when your eyes see the arms still attached and they aren't where they are supposed to be for your real life body, your proprioception causes there to be a disconnect and it causes sickness. Every person is affected differently by VR; some can handle it naturally better than others. However, developers are not content on only making games for those who can handle it in its current incarnation.

